abstract: The song “Respect” helped Aretha Franklin soar to fame and became an anthem for the women’s rights movement. But radio royalties for the song went to its writer, Otis Redding.
snippet: The song “Respect” helped Aretha Franklin soar to fame and became an anthem for the women’s rights movement. But radio royalties for the song went to its writer, Otis Redding.
lead_paragraph: It was Aretha Franklin’s first No. 1 hit, the cry of empowerment that has defined her for generations: “Respect.”

headline_main: How Aretha Franklin’s ‘Respect’ Became a Battle Cry for Musicians Seeking Royalties
headline_print_headline: ‘Respect’ Didn’t Pay Franklin Much. A Copyright Quirk Endures.

abstract: Recorded at a Baptist church in South Los Angeles in 1972, the album is an artist reaching another level.
snippet: Recorded at a Baptist church in South Los Angeles in 1972, the album is an artist reaching another level.
lead_paragraph: Albums don’t “matter,” anymore. But they used to, and when they did, Aretha Franklin, who died on Thursday, was responsible for one of the very best: “Amazing Grace,” a live album recorded over two days in January 1972, at the New Temple Missionary Baptist Church in South Los Angeles.

abstract: The hip-hop master from Run-DMC talks about his new Netflix comedy series, music, religion and his legacy.
snippet: The hip-hop master from Run-DMC talks about his new Netflix comedy series, music, religion and his legacy.
lead_paragraph: Since 2005, Rev Run — a.k.a. Run from Run-DMC, a.k.a Joseph Simmons — has flung open the doors to his opulent Saddle River, N.J., dwelling for shows like “Run’s House,” “Rev Run’s Renovation,” “Rev Run’s Sunday Suppers” and “Rev Runs Around the World.”

abstract: Twitter struggled, and failed, to answer the question of what is allowed on its platform. And Elon Musk dealt with the consequences of having tweeted in the first place.

abstract: The White House cited “erratic” behavior by Mr. Brennan, who has frequently been a fierce critic of the president.
snippet: The White House cited “erratic” behavior by Mr. Brennan, who has frequently been a fierce critic of the president.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — John O. Brennan, the C.I.A. director under President Barack Obama, struck back at President Trump on Thursday for revoking his security clearance, calling the president’s claims of “no collusion” with Russia to influence the 2016 election “hogwash” and arguing that the commander in chief was trying to silence anyone who would dare challenge him.

abstract: The White House cited “erratic” behavior by Mr. Brennan, who has frequently been a fierce critic of the president.
snippet: The White House cited “erratic” behavior by Mr. Brennan, who has frequently been a fierce critic of the president.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump revoked the security clearance of John O. Brennan, the former C.I.A. director under President Barack Obama, on Wednesday in a striking act of retaliation against an outspoken critic. The president threatened to do the same to other former national security officials who have antagonized him.

abstract: Prominent Asian-Americans have been renting out theaters for screenings of the film, hoping to spread demand for more movies with Asian leads.
snippet: Prominent Asian-Americans have been renting out theaters for screenings of the film, hoping to spread demand for more movies with Asian leads.
lead_paragraph: Last month, a group of Silicon Valley venture capital and tech minds gathered for an exclusive dinner at Chef Chu’s, an old-school Chinese restaurant in Los Altos, Calif.

abstract: Cynthia Nixon has been challenging the governor to a debate since May, but until now, he had demurred. He did not debate his 2014 primary challenger.
snippet: Cynthia Nixon has been challenging the governor to a debate since May, but until now, he had demurred. He did not debate his 2014 primary challenger.
lead_paragraph: Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo has agreed to a televised debate against his Democratic rival, Cynthia Nixon, on Aug. 29, two weeks before Primary Day on Sept. 13.
